---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "Love Calculator - Test Your Compatibility Percentages Instantly",
  description: "Want to know if you're a perfect match? See how our unique numerology and string-matching formula works.",
  category: "tool",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Love Calculator - Test Your Compatibility Percentages Instantly",
    "description": "Want to know if you're a perfect match? See how our unique numerology and string-matching formula works.",
    "url": "https://nookienook.com/love-calculator",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "SiliconBased"
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How does the Love Calculator calculate compatibility?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "It uses a custom algorithmic approach combining string character encoding, sum derivations, and pseudo-random hashing to compute a percentage score based on the names inputted. The characters are transformed into numerical values that deterministically generate a 0 to 100% result."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is the Love Calculator scientifically accurate?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. The calculator is meant for entertainment and educational purposes to demonstrate string-hashing methodologies in software development. True romantic compatibility cannot be determined by an algorithm or mathematical formula."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Will the result change if I enter the names in a different order?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. The algorithm normalizes the input by always processing the names in alphabetical order before hashing, ensuring that 'Alice and Bob' returns the exact same score as 'Bob and Alice'."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What programming concepts are used in this Love Calculator?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The tool demonstrates string normalization, character code extraction, deterministic hashing functions, and real-time DOM manipulation using JavaScript event listeners."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does case sensitivity matter when entering names?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No, the inputs are converted to lowercase during normalization, making the algorithm completely case-insensitive. Extra spaces and special characters are also stripped."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];
---
<SiteLayout site="nookienook" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://nookienook.com/love-calculator" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Love Calculator</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Determine compatibility mathematically using our unique string-hashing formula.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="calculator-container">
      <div style="display: flex; gap: 1rem; flex-direction: column; max-width: 400px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div>
          <label for="name1" style="font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; display: block;">Person 1 Name</label>
          <input type="text" id="name1" placeholder="e.g. Alice" />
        </div>
        <div>
          <label for="name2" style="font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; display: block;">Person 2 Name</label>
          <input type="text" id="name2" placeholder="e.g. Bob" />
        </div>
      </div>

      <div id="error-message" style="color: #ef4444; text-align: center; margin-top: 1rem; min-height: 1.5rem;"></div>

      <div class="result-card" id="result-card" style="display: none;">
        <div style="font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Compatibility Score</div>
        <div class="result-value" id="result-value">0%</div>
        <div id="result-description" style="margin-top: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem;"></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="explainer">
      <h2>Understanding the Love Calculator Methodology</h2>
      <p>
        The concept of a "Love Calculator" has existed since the early days of the internet, serving as a fun, interactive way to test the "compatibility" between two individuals. While inherently meant for entertainment, building a robust love calculator provides an excellent opportunity to explore fundamental software engineering concepts, particularly string manipulation, data normalization, and deterministic hashing.
      </p>

      <h3>Algorithmic Approach</h3>
      <p>
        To ensure a consistent and reliable user experience, a love calculator must be deterministic. This means that entering the same two names should always produce the exact same result. Furthermore, the order in which the names are entered shouldn't matter. "Alice and Bob" must yield the same score as "Bob and Alice". Achieving this requires a series of specific algorithmic steps.
      </p>

      <h4>1. Data Normalization</h4>
      <p>
        The first step in our methodology is data normalization. User inputs can be unpredictable, containing unexpected capitalization, trailing spaces, or special characters. To handle this, the algorithm sanitizes the input strings.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Lowercasing:</strong> All characters are converted to lowercase. This ensures that "ALICE" and "alice" are treated identically.</li>
        <li><strong>Whitespace Removal:</strong> Leading, trailing, and internal spaces are stripped. "John Doe" becomes "johndoe".</li>
        <li><strong>Character Filtering:</strong> Non-alphabetic characters are removed using regular expressions, focusing the algorithm purely on the core letters of the names.</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>2. Order Independence</h4>
      <p>
        Once the names are normalized, they must be processed in a way that is independent of their input order. This is achieved by lexicographically sorting the two sanitized names. By comparing the string values and always placing the alphabetically "lesser" string first, we guarantee that any combination of the two names will result in the same composite string before hashing. For example, both inputs ("bob", "alice") and ("alice", "bob") will result in the combined internal string "alicebob".
      </p>

      <h4>3. The Hashing Function</h4>
      <p>
        The core of the calculator is a custom hashing function. Hashing involves taking an input string of arbitrary length and generating a fixed-size numerical value. In our implementation, we use a simple but effective summing mechanism based on the ASCII character codes of the combined names.
      </p>
      <p>
        The algorithm iterates through each character of the combined string. For each character, it retrieves its numeric character code (e.g., 'a' is 97, 'b' is 98). To introduce complexity and pseudo-randomness, these values aren't simply added together. Instead, they are manipulated using bitwise operations and prime number multipliers.
      </p>
      <p>
        A common approach is a variant of the DJB2 algorithm or a simple polynomial rolling hash. In our specific logic:
      </p>
      <pre><code>let hash = 0;
for (let i = 0; i &lt; combinedString.length; i++) &#123;
  const charCode = combinedString.charCodeAt(i);
  hash = ((hash &lt;&lt; 5) - hash) + charCode;
  hash = hash &amp; hash; // Convert to 32bit integer
&#125;</code></pre>

      <h4>4. Deriving the Percentage</h4>
      <p>
        The resulting hash is a seemingly random, potentially large integer (positive or negative). To convert this into a user-friendly percentage (0-100), we apply a modulo operation. By calculating the absolute value of the hash modulo 101, we constrain the output to the desired range.
      </p>
      <pre><code>const percentage = Math.abs(hash) % 101;</code></pre>
      <p>
        This ensures the final score is always between 0% and 100%, providing the determinism and bounding required for the application.
      </p>

      <h3>Why This Matters in Development</h3>
      <p>
        While calculating romantic compatibility is whimsical, the underlying principles are highly relevant in serious software development. Deterministic hashing is critical in load balancing (routing the same user to the same server), caching (generating unique keys based on input parameters), and data integrity verification. String normalization is a fundamental step in processing user data for databases, search indexing, and API integrations.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you are interested in more mathematically rigorous calculations, you might explore our <a href="/integral-calculator">Integral Calculator</a>, which deals with continuous data and area calculations under curves, representing a different spectrum of programmatic problem-solving.
      </p>

      <h3>Expanding the Concept</h3>
      <p>
        Advanced implementations of string comparison algorithms often move beyond simple hashing to incorporate techniques like Levenshtein distance (measuring how many edits it takes to turn one string into another) or Soundex (comparing words based on how they sound rather than how they are spelled). While not implemented in this basic tool, these techniques form the basis of spell-checking algorithms and advanced search engine querying.
      </p>
    </div>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>How does the Love Calculator calculate compatibility?</summary>
        <p>It uses a custom algorithmic approach combining string character encoding, sum derivations, and pseudo-random hashing to compute a percentage score based on the names inputted. The characters are transformed into numerical values that deterministically generate a 0 to 100% result.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is the Love Calculator scientifically accurate?</summary>
        <p>No. The calculator is meant for entertainment and educational purposes to demonstrate string-hashing methodologies in software development. True romantic compatibility cannot be determined by an algorithm or mathematical formula.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Will the result change if I enter the names in a different order?</summary>
        <p>No. The algorithm normalizes the input by always processing the names in alphabetical order before hashing, ensuring that "Alice and Bob" returns the exact same score as "Bob and Alice".</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What programming concepts are used in this Love Calculator?</summary>
        <p>The tool demonstrates string normalization, character code extraction, deterministic hashing functions, and real-time DOM manipulation using JavaScript event listeners.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Does case sensitivity matter when entering names?</summary>
        <p>No, the inputs are converted to lowercase during normalization, making the algorithm completely case-insensitive. Extra spaces and special characters are also stripped.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
      const name1Input = document.getElementById('name1');
      const name2Input = document.getElementById('name2');
      const resultCard = document.getElementById('result-card');
      const resultValue = document.getElementById('result-value');
      const resultDesc = document.getElementById('result-description');
      const errorMessage = document.getElementById('error-message');

      function calculateLove() {
        const raw1 = name1Input.value;
        const raw2 = name2Input.value;

        if (!raw1 && !raw2) {
          resultCard.style.display = 'none';
          errorMessage.textContent = '';
          return;
        }

        if (!raw1 || !raw2) {
          resultCard.style.display = 'none';
          errorMessage.textContent = 'Please enter both names to see compatibility.';
          return;
        }

        const clean1 = raw1.toLowerCase().replace(/[^a-z]/g, '');
        const clean2 = raw2.toLowerCase().replace(/[^a-z]/g, '');

        if (!clean1 || !clean2) {
           resultCard.style.display = 'none';
           errorMessage.textContent = 'Names must contain at least one letter.';
           return;
        }

        errorMessage.textContent = '';

        // Order independent
        const sorted = [clean1, clean2].sort();
        const combined = sorted[0] + sorted[1];

        // DJB2 Hash
        let hash = 0;
        for (let i = 0; i < combined.length; i++) {
          const charCode = combined.charCodeAt(i);
          hash = ((hash << 5) - hash) + charCode;
          hash = hash & hash;
        }

        const percentage = Math.abs(hash) % 101;

        resultValue.textContent = `${percentage}%`;
        resultCard.style.display = 'block';

        if (percentage >= 90) {
          resultDesc.textContent = "A perfect match! Mathematically inevitable.";
        } else if (percentage >= 70) {
          resultDesc.textContent = "Very high compatibility. Looking good!";
        } else if (percentage >= 50) {
          resultDesc.textContent = "Solid potential. There's a decent connection.";
        } else if (percentage >= 30) {
          resultDesc.textContent = "It might take some work, but anything is possible.";
        } else {
          resultDesc.textContent = "Statistically challenging, but love defies math sometimes.";
        }
      }

      name1Input.addEventListener('input', calculateLove);
      name2Input.addEventListener('input', calculateLove);
    });
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .subtitle { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .calculator-container { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0; }
    input, select { background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding: 0.75rem 1rem; border-radius: 8px; width: 100%; font-size: 1rem; }
    input:focus, select:focus { outline: none; border-color: var(--accent-color); box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 20%, transparent); }
    button { background: var(--accent-color); color: white; border: none; padding: 0.75rem 2rem; border-radius: 8px; font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; font-size: 1rem; }
    button:hover { opacity: 0.9; }
    .result-card { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 10%, transparent); border: 1px solid var(--accent-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; text-align: center; }
    .result-value { font-size: 2.5rem; font-weight: 800; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .faq-section details { margin: 1rem 0; padding: 1rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-section summary { font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; }
    .explainer { line-height: 1.6; margin-top: 3rem; margin-bottom: 3rem; }
    .explainer h2 { margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--accent-color); font-size: 1.75rem; }
    .explainer h3 { margin-top: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-size: 1.25rem; }
    .explainer h4 { margin-top: 1.25rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .explainer p { margin-bottom: 1.25rem; color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .explainer ul { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; padding-left: 1.5rem; color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .explainer li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .explainer pre { background: var(--bg-color); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px; overflow-x: auto; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .explainer code { font-family: monospace; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .explainer a { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: none; }
    .explainer a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
